## Paths forward (mutually exclusive — pick one before continuing)

When the verdict is `partial` or `preliminary`, two paths are typically available. State
both up front so the author can decide before reading the detailed findings.

- **Path A (narrow the claim).** Rewrite the headline / abstract so it no longer depends
  on the high-severity findings. List which specific abstract sentences change and to
  what. This is the lower-cost path; it does not require re-running experiments.
- **Path B (close the gaps).** Run the specific follow-up experiments that resolve the
  high-severity findings, then re-issue the verdict. This is the higher-cost path; it
  preserves the original claim's scope.

For `ready` verdicts, this section may be omitted. For `preliminary` verdicts on
rejection notebooks, Path A is usually narrowing the rejection's scope; Path B is
running the experiments that would either confirm a stronger rejection or upgrade the
result to `partial` / `supported`.

